Saw it in 4-D at Cinema Q, 13 days after Christmas, with a Hardy Boys’ exclusive soundtrack and sound design. The only way this movie is meant to be seen. It’s hard to fathom how insanely good they are after SEVENTY FIVE YEARS of doing what they do. Every strike of the pot, oscillation of the fan, snip of the scissors, and gleam of the flashlight through colorful plastic bags to simulate the aurora borealis was so impeccably meditated and…
Optimism’s poster child!! Except if you’re Hugh Grant!!

"The Square is a sanctuary of trust and caring. Within it we all share equal rights and obligations"Kind of freaking brilliant. Chalking this up to just being a low-hanging-fruit critique of modern art I think is missing the point. Reads like an anthology of dark sketches taking place in different rooms of the new Ed Ruscha installation but without the plaques to invent some bullshit about what it all means. The pretentiousness we build up tall around high art…
Most impressive thing about this is every scene got so many heads

Score and cinematography went absolutely feral. Oh yeah play me that big sweeping music and show me the gd sunlight if you want me to fall in love so badly. Still the rom of it all wasn’t hitting for me (boy, I know) until that last scene, and then… oh man…
What a world of love. Had me walking out of the theater being extra sensitive to the way the cold hugs the most lonely of tree trunks, the wind kisses the most rogue of leaves
